____Some of us are using 56K modems for our internet access. The code block below fits in at lines 170-2 in the "calc-eta" block. The days option could be of use to someone with a 256K (quarter-meg) DSL that is trying to get a 3GB movie. Thank you for a nice chunk of Python - it works well even with my skinny pipe.\\
R.Sugg

P.S. Your posting software has expanded the tabs to eight (8) columns. I&#x27;ll check back in a few days to see if you need anything more. R

{{{\\
#!python

h1. Patch to "calc-eta" near lines 170-2 :
h1. 
h1. The following code is rem&#x27;d out due to this tool being used in a dial-up environment.
#R.Sugg 13 June 09

h1. if eta_mins > 99:
h1. return &#x27;--:--&#x27;
h1. return &#x27;%02d:%02d&#x27; % (eta_mins, eta_secs)
h1. 
h1. Mark I - While loops, Mark II - divmod(...)
h1. 
h1. eta_hrs = 0
h1. while eta_mins > 59 :
h1. eta_hrs += 1
h1. eta_mins -= 60
{code}
	tmp_mins = eta_mins
	(eta_hrs, eta_mins) = divmod(tmp_mins, 60)
{code}

h1. 
h1. eta_days = 0
h1. while eta_hrs > 23 :
h1. eta_days += 1
h1. eta_hrs -= 24
{code}
	tmp_hrs = eta_hrs
	(eta_days, eta_hrs) = divmod(tmp_hrs, 24)
{code}

h1. 
h1. The format strings have spaces added to blank out the longer pre-cursors
h1. (Mk.I). Padded tags moved outside for ease of maintenance (Mk.II).
h1. 
{code}
	if eta_days > 99 :
		return "INSANE DOWNLOAD IN PROGRESS (100+ days) ..."
	elif eta_days > 0 :
		return &#x27;%02d:%02d:%02d:%02d %s&#x27; % (eta_days, eta_hrs, eta_mins, eta_secs,"[DHMS]")
	elif eta_hrs > 0 :
		return &#x27;%02d:%02d:%02d %s&#x27; % (eta_hrs, eta_mins, eta_secs, "[HMS]    ")
	else :
		return &#x27;%02d:%02d %s&#x27; % (eta_mins, eta_secs, "[MS]        ")
